Mafdet's assessment of the Chromatic Circle is commercial: synthesis practitioners who can
address novel cargo hazards, weather phenomena, or material interactions are valuable to maritime
operations. The Strandline Compact does not distinguish between Axiomatic and Circle-lineage
practitioners for licensing purposes—the relevant credential is demonstrated competence, not
school affiliation. Mafdet's Shrine of the First Claw has historically been willing to consult
Circle-lineage practitioners on unusual relic and artifact assessments where single-school
analysis proves insufficient. The harbor arbitration courts do not privilege either school's
analysis in expert testimony—both are admitted and weighed against each other on the merits.
Mafdet's pragmatism on this question is occasionally in tension with Midgaard's Axiomatic
institutional partners, who prefer that expert testimony in formal proceedings come from
credentialed Axiomatic practitioners.

